The paper discusses a strategy for training DNN policies based on human corrective feedback, which falls under the category of Interactive Machine Learning (IML). The paper also mentions the use of Deep Reinforcement Learning (DRL) and Deep Neural Networks (DNNs), which are commonly associated with the sub-categories cs.LG (Machine Learning) and cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence). The experiments involve simulated and real-world robotic environments, which suggests the sub-category cs.RO (Robotics). The paper also mentions the use of state spaces and visual inputs, which are associated with the sub-categories cs.CV (Computer Vision) and cs.HC (Human-Computer Interaction). Therefore, the most likely sub-categories are cs.LG, cs.AI, cs.RO, cs.HC, and cs.CV, in that order.
